eons-a decades-long resistance that led to the Inter-American Court of Human Rights and back to the frontlines of Paraguay's ranching frontier. The Indigenous communities at the heart of this story employ a dialectics of disruption by working with and against the law to unsettle enduring racial geographies and rebuild territorial relations, albeit with uncertain outcomes. Joel E. Correia shows that Enxet and Sanapaná peoples enact environmental justice otherwise: moving beyond juridical solutions to harm by maintaining collective lifeways and resistance amid radical social-ecological change. Correia's ethnography advances debates about environmental racism, ethics of engaged research, and Indigenous resurgence on Latin America's settler frontiers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnvironmental justicezChaco Boreal (Paraguay and Bolivia) 0aEnvironmental justicezChaco Boreal (Paraguay and Bolivia). 0aIndians of South AmericaxLand tenurezChaco Boreal (Paraguay and Bolivia) 0aIndians of South AmericaxLand tenurezChaco Boreal (Paraguay and Bolivia). 0aIndians of South AmericaxPolitical activityzChaco Boreal (Paraguay and Bolivia) 0aIndians of South AmericaxPolitical activityzChaco Boreal (Paraguay and Bolivia). 0aSettler colonialismzChaco Boreal (Paraguay and Bolivia) 0aSettler colonialismzChaco Boreal (Paraguay and Bolivia). 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Scien